A step too far
Oct 2024 • Couples
The bell tower is all that remains of the Church of Saint-Jacques-de-la-Boucherie (so named because it was funded by the brotherhood of butchers—and to distinguish it from the church of the same name on the other side of the Seine). Confiscated during the French Revolution, it was sold and its stones used as a quarry for other buildings. There was a condition, however: that the tower not be torn down. In the mid-sixteenth century, the mathematician Blaise Pascal had conducted experiments there on air pressure, his statue at the base commemorating that work—although Pascal is much better known for the “Pensées,” his unfinished apologia for Christianity. Now meticulously restored, the tower is open for guided tours from May to November. But, with 300 steps to the top—more than the Whispering Gallery of St. Paul’s or the dome of Sacré Cœur, I’ve had to forgo the view.
Written November 7, 2024

What remains of a 16th-century church along Rue de Rivoli
Aug 2024 • Couples
It is always nice passing by and seeing Tour Saint-Jacques (St. James Tower) situated in a square by the same name when passing by Rue de Rivoli. Originally part of a large 16th-century church that was destroyed in the 18th-century, what is left standing is the Flamboyant Gothic tower which seems out of place on its own yet remains nice to look at if you enjoy this architectural style and are visiting this area of the city.

Old medieval tower remnant of church
Jul 2024 • Family
The last remaining vestige of a church which stood here until the Revolution. The tower was restored within the last 20+ years and they've done an excellent job. Visiting the interior and climbing to the top is by prebooked tour only. If you do book the tour, keep in mind it's 300+ steps to the top on a winding staircase from medieval times. They warn you in advance that if you're easily dizzy, out of shape, etc., then DON'T do it. You'll ruin the tour for others who've come prepared. Bring some water. The tour is excellent and takes you to two separate floors before ascending to the roof and spectacular views of Paris. Tours available in French or English. It's a seasonal tour usually from mid/late May - late August/early September. Easily reached via metro.
Written July 20, 2024

UNESCO Heritage Sight
Apr 2024 • Solo
Tour Saint-Jacques has been a landmark of Paris since the 16th century, when it was part of the Church of Saint-Jacques-de-la-Boucherie. The church was ravaged during the French Revolution, but the tower is still standing strong and has been included in the glorious family of the UNESCO heritage sights.

Unfortunately, I never had a chance to climb to the top of the tower, so I can’t speak about it, but the views from the little garden around it are spectacular. The gargoyles are still there😊
